Local Engagement as a Countermeasure against Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments resemble each other everywhere in the West.
The leaderships of the once dominant parties fluctuate between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to recognize a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their opponents' supporters as "pitiable," as Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too intimidated by the populist wave to launch a counteroffensive.
Yet neither denial nor complacency will resolve the stagnant political situation.
The Progressives must reorganize, and this begins with diagnosing the inadequacies of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the worsening environmental crises, the increasing geographical inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are alone in the forest and wonder where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and the policy of governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the growing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet before the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national prime minister had implemented tax reductions based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In the year 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the questioners then became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct against women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At the time, Macron's stance made him a target of jokes by his opponents; however, the laughter of those opponents quickly faded with the emergence of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not sufficient.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer on the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that sees democracy as a marketplace composed of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and retain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological edge over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to vote, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer holds.
Today, citizens refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education came new demands for participation.
The voters want to be treated as political actors and not as pawns in the chess game of others.
In addition, governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the harsh lessons we had to learn in the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions from national governments alone.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at sub- and supranational levels.
Finally, technology has lowered the barriers to entry for political participation, so traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and entrenched support networks.
Whoever can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well no longer needs a century-old party apparatus.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
With La République En Marche!, we refer to these as local citizen projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems and thereby strengthening communities.
Such projects should today be seen as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding avenues for political and local engagement will be essential to its appeal.
And by daily demonstrating their reform policies "live," the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what you have to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the harsh lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Re-establishing the connection to voters' concerns therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics at the local level.
